\end_inset

 Substituting Eqs.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:Hcj}}$
\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:Hci}}$
\end_inset

) back into Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:EM_rho}}$
\end_inset

) yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
-i\hbar\frac{d}{dt}\rho_{ee}^{\boldsymbol{i}\boldsymbol{j}}= & H_{0}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}\boldsymbol{j}}\left\langle c_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}^{\dagger}c_{\boldsymbol{i}}\right\rangle -H_{0}^{\boldsymbol{i}\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\left\langle c_{\boldsymbol{j}}^{\dagger}c_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\right\rangle \\
 & +\frac{1}{2}v^{\alpha j}\left(\left\langle c_{\boldsymbol{j}}^{\dagger}c_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}^{\dagger}c_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}c_{\boldsymbol{i}}\right\rangle -\left\langle c_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}^{\dagger}c_{\boldsymbol{j}}^{\dagger}c_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}c_{\boldsymbol{i}}\right\rangle \right)\\
 & +\frac{1}{2}v^{\alpha i}\left(\left\langle c_{\boldsymbol{j}}^{\dagger}c_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}^{\dagger}c_{\boldsymbol{i}}c_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\right\rangle -\left\langle c_{\boldsymbol{j}}^{\dagger}c_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}^{\dagger}c_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}c_{\boldsymbol{i}}\right\rangle \right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Coming back to the rDM definitions and commutating the terms it reads
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
i\hbar\frac{d}{dt}\rho_{ee}^{\boldsymbol{i}\boldsymbol{j}}= & -H_{0}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}\boldsymbol{j}}\rho_{ee}^{\boldsymbol{i}\boldsymbol{\alpha}}+H_{0}^{\boldsymbol{i}\boldsymbol{\alpha}}\rho_{ee}^{\boldsymbol{\alpha}\boldsymbol{j}}\nonumber \\
 & -\left(v^{\alpha j}-v^{\alpha i}\right)\left\langle c_{\boldsymbol{j}}^{\dagger}c_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}^{\dagger}c_{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}c_{\boldsymbol{i}}\right\rangle 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Notice, however, that the interaction term will give rise to expectation
 values of four-operators.
 For this, we introduce a mean-field approximation where we assume the two-parti
cle expectation value to simply behave as a product of two one-particle
 expectation values.
 From this mean-field decoupling we can then make use of 
\emph on
Wick's theorem
\emph default
, yielding
